20s, which may be best understood not as the Jazz Age or the Age of Prohibition, but as the Age of the Klan. Ku Klux Kulture gives us an unsettling glimpse into the past, arguing that the Klan did not die so much as melt into America's prevailing culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4a1920s. 4aKu Klux Klan. 4aanti-Catholicism. 4aanti-Semitism. 4acultural pluralism. 4aethnonationalism. 4aimagined community. 4apopular culture. 4awhite supremacism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226376295423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226376295.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles